### 5. Error Handling and Loading States

```javascript
import { Button, Spin, Alert } from 'antd';
import { useState } from 'react';

function LoadingExample() {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  const handleSubmit = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    setError(null);

    try {
      // API call here
      await someAsyncOperation();
    } catch (err) {
      setError(err.message);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      {error && (
        <Alert
          message="Error"
          description={error}
          type="error"
          closable
          style={{ marginBottom: 16 }}
        />
      )}
      <Spin spinning={loading}>
        <Button type="primary" onClick={handleSubmit}>
          Submit
        </Button>
      </Spin>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Useful Resources

- [Official Documentation](https://ant.design/docs/react/introduce)
- [Component Demo](https://ant.design/components/overview/)
- [Design Language](https://ant.design/docs/spec/introduce)
- [Ant Design Pro](https://pro.ant.design/) - Enterprise-class UI solutions
- [Ant Design Mobile](https://mobile.ant.design/) - Mobile UI components

## Conclusion

Ant Design provides a comprehensive set of React components that follow design principles and best practices. By following this tutorial, you should have a solid foundation to start building beautiful and functional React applications with Ant Design.

Remember to:
- Keep your imports clean and specific
- Use the built-in theme system for consistent styling
- Follow responsive design patterns
- Handle loading and error states appropriately
- Refer to the official documentation for detailed API references

Happy coding with Ant Design! 🚀", "mode": "append"}}

